Indeed, words/phrases implies enough - but during a clash (at least for me personally) implications give me a nugget of doubt; for that reason I prefer clear cut rules (and, as a non-native English speaker I did not realize that phrase is always multiple words, which might additionally explain my doubt).

I do really admire how you managed to put an actual existing thing (the Remote Associative Test) into the size of a clash - it is certainly doable within 15 minutes thanks to your set-up after all. However, it almost feels a shame to put this one in a Clash: during the Clash no one bothers about the interesting lessons, it is just eyes on the timer. So, that makes me wonder: can some aspects be added to increase the difficulty, to push it just over the clash/puzzle border? As a puzzle, it feels very nice to deal with some real-life aspect and getting a grasp on it - even coding a solution on it yourself. Some suggestions for added difficulty:
- Include 'Not valid', for situations where no common word can be found;
- Include some not valid situations that seem valid (rice bag / price tag / trice; answer would be rice with my current code), but include a rule that the common word cannot be in the middle of a word (or some other phrasing of rules that rule out rice as part of price tag);
- Add the synonym option (from your Wikipedia option: same/tennis/head, with answer match, because of matchhead, tennis match and same being synonym for match), by including a thesaurus.

---But it is totally up to you, and if some others start commenting 'all is well' I might even feel comfortable with approving it in its current state, under the assumption I was just slow in yesterday's trial.
